import java.util.*;  // Import necessary classes from Java's Standard Library package for handling data structures such as lists, sets etc., used here just show how JDBC can be done and not required by A03 injection attacks (i.e., Data Manipulation) using PreparedStatement is better than raw SQL queries
  
public class java_47089_JDBCQueryHandler_A03 {  // The start of our Java Program - Class 'VanillaJava' starts from the line number where this program will run, we call it as a starting point for all other code. This serves to organize and keep things organized in source files (as per good programming practices)
   public static void main(String[] args){  // We start by creating our Java Program - Method 'main' is the entry of any java program if there are no errors, it will execute from here onwards which we do not call explicitly as for other codes but they serve to organize and keep things organized in source files.
      try {   // Here starting point where a block begins that can throw an exception (any error occurs within this scope) - This is the mechanism by Java's 'try-catch'-blocks – if any errors occur, control will jump here after catching them with catch blocks below which we provide for A03 injection attacks
         Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection("jdbc:your_db", "user","pass"); // Get a connection to the database - The driver name (the MySQL JDBC Connector) is not required as it's part of Java Standard Library, but should be used in case you want different type drivers
         String query = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE email=?";  // A SQL Query for getting data from DB. It includes a placeholder ('?') which will replace by the value passed into this method - Again not required to follow best practices of preventing injection attacks (i.e., using PreparedStatements)
         PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement(query);  // A 'Prepare Statement' is an instance that can be used with a Connection object which allows us the ability by specifying what data we want to fetch from DB, then execute this statement - Again not required for preventing SQL Injection attacks
         String emailToVerify = "test@email.com";  // The Value of Email you wish to verify (i.e., row in table) if exist on Database otherwise it will be null when calling method below due Security Sensitive Operations related A03_Injections attack which is done by providing a value for email parameter
         pstmt.setString(1,emailToVerify);  // Setting the '?' placeholder to some data - Again not required preventing SQL Injection attacks but used here just as example of usage where you may want more placeholders and their respective values in actual use cases (i.e., using PreparedStatements)
         ResultSet rs = pstmt.executeQuery();  // Execute the query, get a result set - This is done by calling 'pstmt'. Here we fetch data from DB as per our SQL Query above and store them into list of objects which are manipulated later on (as seen below). Security Sensitive Operations related A03_Injection attacks here due to use PreparedStatements.
         while(rs.next()){ // While there is a row in the result set - This loop will execute as long rows exist with our Query, if not it means no data was found for that particular email (i.e., Data Manipulation) and Security Sensitive Operation related A03_Injection attack which we do here using PreparedStatements
            String userEmail = rs.getString("email");  // Fetching the 'user' column from each row of data fetched - Again not required preventing SQL Injection attacks due to use prepared statement (i.e., avoiding directly inject value into query via parameterized queries) and used here just as example
            System.out.println(userEmail);  	// Print out email if exist in Database, otherwise it will be null or print nothing when calling this method below because of Security Sensitive Operations related A03_Injection attack which is done by passing a value for user object and then check whether the returned data from DB exists
         }  // Ending while loop due to Data Manipulation secure operations (i.e., no more than required until we have checked all rows with our query) because it prevents SQL Injections attacks in following lines, this is done by using PreparedStatements instead of directly inject value into queries via parameterized and placeholders
      } catch(SQLException ex){ // Catch Block for catching any exceptions if an error occurs - Any exception thrown within the block will be caught here. This serves as a mechanism to handle errors effectively, notifying developers about what went wrong (i.e., Debugging) due Security Sensitive Operations related A03_Injection attacks
         System.out.println("Error in database operation: " + ex); // Print out the exception message for debuging purposes - Again done here to protect against SQL Injections Attacks via PreparedStatements and catch block of exceptions is used above which are not required but provided as examples about how you can use it
      }  finally {   // This part will execute no matter what (whether an error occurred or the code completed normally), this serves for cleanup tasks - Again done here to prevent SQL Injections attacks in following lines, we do avoid direct injections of values into queries via placeholders and parameterized statements. As it uses PreparedStatements
         if(conn != null){   // Make sure that database connection is not closed when an error occurs or program finishes executing - This prevents the leakage issue (i., SQL Injection Attacks) due to using try-catch blocks for exception handling and close of Connection Objects, which we do here in finally block
            conn.close();  // Close DB Connections safely because any other code that uses this connection could have a problem if not closed properly - Again done at the end since no more logic is present within it apart from closing connections (i., SQL Injection attacks) due to use of try-catch blocks for exception handling
         }   // Ending finally block as part of our program, all operations here are secure against A03_Injections attack and thus should be avoided by following best practices. These codes only do basic tasks that the user requests (i., minimizing security risk) due to follow up on avoiding SQL Injection attacks via PreparedStatements
      }  // Ending main method as part of our program, all operations here are secure against A03_Injections attack and thus should be avoided by following best practices. These codes only do basic tasks that the user requests (i., minimizing security risk) due to follow up on avoiding SQL Injection attacks via PreparedStatements
   }  // Ending Class 'VanillaJava' as part of our program, all operations here are secure against A03_Injections attack and thus should be avoided by following best practices. These codes only do basic tasks that the user requests (i., minimizing security risk) due to follow up on avoiding SQL Injection attacks via PreparedStatements
}  // Ending Java Program as part of our program, all operations here are secure against A03_Injections attack and thus should be avoided by following best practices. These codes only do basic tasks that the user requests (i., minimizing security risk) due to follow up on avoiding SQL Injection attacks via PreparedStatements